Since you need **three** themes, use the **ResourceDictionary swap** approach — `AppThemeBinding` only supports two (light/dark).

## 1. Create three theme dictionaries with matching keys

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBg">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#333333</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#2196F3</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml** — same keys, dark values:
```xml
    <Color x:Key="PageBg">#121212</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#EEEEEE</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#BB86FC</Color>
```

**Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml** — same keys, high-contrast values:
```xml
    <Color x:Key="PageBg">Black</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">Yellow</Color>
```

Each needs a code-behind that calls `InitializeComponent()`:
```csharp
namespace MyApp.Themes;
public partial class LightTheme : ResourceDictionary
{
    public LightTheme() => InitializeComponent();
}
```

## 2. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere (not `StaticResource`)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBg}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
    <Button Text="Go"   BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource Accent}" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 3. Theme-switching service

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme()
        };

        var merged = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        merged.Clear();
        merged.Add(theme);

        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", themeName);
    }

    public static void ApplySaved()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
        ApplyTheme(saved);
    }
}
```

## 4. Apply on startup (App.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplySaved();
}
```

## 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string theme)
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

## Key gotchas

- **Every `x:Key` must exist in all three dictionaries** — a missing key silently falls back to defaults.
- **Use `DynamicResource`**, never `StaticResource`, or values won't update on swap.
- **Android**: ensure `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or theme events won't fire and the activity restarts on OS theme change.
